replyContent: There is only one case where the app cannot save: If your phone/tablet has 2 storage devices (internal memory and SD card slot for example), only one of them is writable by the app due to Android security restrictions, so move your games or save folder into the correct location to get saves working.

I've tried many and this is the best one by far, accentuated by the recent addition of cheats. The real time clock works as it's supposed to. There are many configurable options such as the ability to disable linear filtering (a.k.a. washed out appearance). Although some games such as Pokemon require changing the video settings to be optimal, as with the default settings, the image tears with movement. Setting the screen size to integer fixes this with only a slight reduction in video size. Where the emulator falls short is its ability to emulate games with darker colour pallets. Parts of the game with darker colours or outlines appear to smudge with movement. Pokemon Crystal for example; with the night-time colour pallet, the darker outline around the houses and people smudge with movement, giving them the visual impression of expanding in size. More noticeable are the surrounding trees, which to the eye appear change colour with movement. My point is that while it isn't perfect, it is the best and well worth the cost to support the dev.
